Details of Statistical Analysis

Covariate Selection

Prior Distribution Definitions

In defining prior distributions, we generally followed suggestions from previous literature.1–3 Specifically, we defined 4 sets of priors for each outcome:

Neutral prior: mean of 0 and standard deviation of 0.35, centering around an OR of 1 and 95% of the the probability mass for the OR between 0.5 to 1.99.

Left hemisphere prior: mean of -0.22 and standard deviation of 0.175, centering around an OR of 0.8 and 95% of the the probability mass for the OR between 0.57 to 1.13.

Right hemisphere prior: mean of 0.18 and standard deviation of 0.175, centering around an OR of 1.2 and 95% of the the probability mass for the OR between 0.85 to 1.69.

Flat prior: most mimics a frequentist analysis

Alternative Handling of Missing Data

mRS Data

with_dir(here(), tar_load(m_posterior_mrs_90_canonical))

mod <- avg_predictions(m_posterior_mrs_90_canonical, by = "ich_laterality")

data <- mod |>
  select(group, ich_laterality, estimate) |>
  as_tibble() |>
  mutate(estimate = estimate * 100)

mrs_90 <- m_posterior_mrs_90_canonical |>
  spread_draws(b_ich_lateralityRight) |>
  mutate(ich_right_or = exp(b_ich_lateralityRight)) |>
  summarize(
    or_1 = sum(ich_right_or > 1) / n(),
    or_1.1 = sum(ich_right_or > 1.1) / n(),
    or_1.2 = sum(ich_right_or > 1.2) / n(),
    rope = sum(ich_right_or < 1.05 & ich_right_or > 0.95) / n()
  )
